SIMPLE: state
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: State
<hw>State</hw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stat</ets>, OF. <ets>estat</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧tat</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>status</ets> a standing, position, fr. <ets>stare</ets>,
<ets>statum</ets>, to stand. See <er>Stand</er>, and cf.
<er>Estate</er>, <er>Status</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
circumstances or condition of a being or thing at any given
time.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>State</qex> is a term nearly synonymous with
⟦ldquo⟧mode,⟦rdquo⟧ but of a meaning more extensive, and is not
exclusively limited to the mutable and contingent.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Declare the past and present <qex>state</qex> of things.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Keep the <qex>state</qex> of the question in your eye.</q>
<rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Rank; condition; quality; <as>as, the <ex>state</ex>
of honor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy honor, <qex>state</qex>, and seat is due to me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Condition of prosperity or grandeur; wealthy or
prosperous circumstances; social importance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She instructed him how he should keep <qex>state</qex>, and yet
with a modest sense of his misfortunes.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Can this imperious lord forget to reign,⟦br⟧
Quit all his <qex>state</qex>, descend, and serve again?</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Appearance of grandeur or dignity; pomp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where least of <qex>state</qex> there most of love is shown.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A chair with a canopy above it, often standing on a
dais; a seat of dignity; also, the canopy itself.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His high throne, . . . under <qex>state</qex>⟦br⟧
Of richest texture spread.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When he went to court, he used to kick away the <qex>state</qex>,
and sit down by his prince cheek by jowl.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Estate; possession.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Daniel.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your <qex>state</qex>, my lord, again is yours.</q>
<rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A person of high rank.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Latimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Any body of men united by profession, or
constituting a community of a particular character; <as>as, the civil
and ecclesiastical <ex>states</ex>, or the lords spiritual and temporal
and the commons, in Great Britain</as>. Cf. <er>Estate</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 6.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>The principal persons in a government.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bold design⟦br⟧
Pleased highly those infernal <qex>states</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>The bodies that constitute the legislature of a
country; <as>as, the <ex>States</ex>-general of Holland</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>A form of government which is not monarchial, as a
republic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Well monarchies may own religion's name,⟦br⟧
But <qex>states</qex> are atheists in their very fame.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>A political body, or body politic; the whole body
of people who are united under one government, whatever may be the form
of the government; a nation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Municipal law is a rule of conduct prescribed by the supreme power
in a <qex>state</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Puritans in the reign of Mary, driven from their homes, sought
an asylum in Geneva, where they found a <qex>state</qex> without a king,
and a church without a bishop.</q> <rj><qau>R. Choate.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>In the United States, one of the commonwealths, or
bodies politic, the people of which make up the body of the nation, and
which, under the national constitution, stand in certain specified
relations with the national government, and are invested, as
commonwealths, with full power in their several spheres over all matters
not expressly inhibited.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The term <xex>State</xex>, in its technical sense, is
used in distinction from the federal system, <it>i. e.</it>, the
government of the United States.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <def>Highest and stationary condition, as that of
maturity between growth and decline, or as that of crisis between the
increase and the abating of a disease; height; acme.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ When <xex>state</xex> is joined with another word, or
used adjectively, it denotes public, or what belongs to the community or
body politic, or to the government; also, what belongs to the States
severally in the American Union; as, <xex>state</xex> affairs;
<xex>state</xex> policy; <xex>State</xex> laws of Iowa.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Nascent state</b></col>. <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Nascent</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Secretary of state</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Secretary</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3.</cd> -- <col><b>State
barge</b></col><cd>a royal barge, or a barge belonging to a
government.</cd> -- <col><b>State bed</b></col>, <cd>an elaborately
carved or decorated bed.</cd> -- <col><b>State carriage</b></col>, <cd>a
highly decorated carriage for officials going in state, or taking part
in public processions.</cd> -- <col><b>State paper</b></col>, <cd>an
official paper relating to the interests or government of a state.</cd>
<au>Jay.</au> -- <col><b>State prison</b></col>, <cd>a public prison or
penitentiary; -- called also <altname>State's prison</altname>.</cd> --
<col><b>State prisoner</b></col>, <cd>one in confinement, or under
arrest, for a political offense.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>State
rights</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>States' rights</b></col></mcol>,
<cd>the rights of the several independent States, as distinguished from
the rights of the Federal government. It has been a question as to what
rights have been vested in the general government.</cd>
<mark>[U.S.]</mark> -- <col><b>State's evidence</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Probator</er>, 2, and under <er>Evidence</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>State
sword</b></col>, <cd>a sword used on state occasions, being borne before
a sovereign by an attendant of high rank.</cd> -- <col><b>State
trial</b></col>, <cd>a trial of a person for a political offense.</cd>
-- <col><b>States of the Church</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Ecclesiastical</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>State</er>, <er>Situation</er>,
<er>Condition</er>.</syn> <usage><xex>State</xex> is the generic term,
and denotes in general the mode in which a thing stands or exists. The
<xex>situation</xex> of a thing is its state in reference to external
objects and influences; its <xex>condition</xex> is its internal state,
or what it is in itself considered. Our <xex>situation</xex> is good or
bad as outward things bear favorably or unfavorably upon us; our
<xex>condition</xex> is good or bad according to the state we are
actually in as respects our persons, families, property, and other
things which comprise our sources of enjoyment.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I do not, brother,⟦br⟧
Infer as if I thought my sister's <qex>state</qex>⟦br⟧
Secure without all doubt or controversy.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We hoped to enjoy with ease what, in our <qex>situation</qex>,
might be called the luxuries of life.</q> <rj><qau>Cook.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And, O, what man's <qex>condition</qex> can be worse⟦br⟧
Than his whom plenty starves and blessings curse?</q>
<rj><qau>Cowley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>State</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: State
<hw>State</hw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Stately.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Belonging to the state, or body politic;
public.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>State</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: State
<hw>State</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To set; to settle; to
establish.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I myself, though meanest <qex>stated</qex>,⟦br⟧
And in court now almost hated.</q> <rj><qau>Wither.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who calls the council, <qex>states</qex> the certain day.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To express the particulars of; to set down in detail
or in gross; to represent fully in words; to narrate; to recite; <as>as,
to <ex>state</ex> the facts of a case, one's opinion,
etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To state it</b></col>. <cd>To assume state or
dignity.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Rarely dressed up, and taught
<xex>to state it</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Beau. & Fl.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>State</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: State
<hw>State</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A statement; also, a document
containing a statement.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir W.
Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Statecraft</ent>⟦br⟧
